It's not that obvious. This monster just let out a loud roar and tried to charge at Sazalin. Thank goodness, Sazalin may be big in size but is still agile, and he managed to dodge it just in time. However, Nexi couldn't help but scream out in fright and almost slid down from Sazalin's smooth scales.
“How do we kill them?” Nexi shouted.
“Aim for their heads!”
“This is too difficult!”
Sazalin let out a loud roar, circled around, and flew towards the mountain he called home. The black monster followed closely behind, but when it was attacked from behind by flames, it looked flustered. This monster still hasn't realized it's got another opponent. Sazalin slowed down his speed, then struck the monster's head with his tail, causing it to veer off course, and the monster became even more flustered.
Monster let out a deafening roar, with a screeching sound in its throat, flying straight up and spitting out something into the air. Suddenly, the surroundings became pitch black, as if the monster was sucking in the light from the sky, replacing it with eternal darkness.
Sasarin's vision went black, and he tried to step back, but he bumped into a tree branch and fell onto the open ground. The monster seemed to know exactly where Sasarin had fallen, and flew straight towards him, bringing the dark cloud with it.
"Kael!" Tenruk shouted as he flew out of the cloud, beginning to circle, trying to find Nisi and Sasarin in the darkness below. "What do we do? Kael...? Kael, where are you?"
Nisi struggled to her feet. She was sure she had broken her bones, but her strange, unnatural healing ability was already kicking in. Sasarin's situation was different, though; he was lying on the ground, powerless, using a tree he had knocked over as support. Nisi made an effort to walk towards Sasarin, but her vision was a complete black, barely able to see anything. There were terrifying shadows everywhere, with something screaming in the shadows.
A terrifying rod-like tail suddenly slammed onto the ground, sending Nisi tumbling to the ground. She noticed the tail was swinging wildly, but the target seemed to not be her. Nisi barely saw that the monster was roaring, using its claws to frantically scratch at the shadows it had created. Something was moving in the darkness, waiting to strike at the monster.
Suddenly, a gunshot rang out, and the monster instantly fell silent, lying motionless on the ground. The surrounding darkness dissipated, revealing the truth of the situation. Cayel stood on the monster's corpse, holding his rifle and gasping for breath.
“That's...this is one of the most strange shadow jumps I've ever done...Tanto Cartalon...” Cayel gasped out between ragged breaths. For some reason, his eyes flashed with black light, and a dark energy surged through his body. But just as Cayel opened his mouth to speak, his organic armor restored its color, and his eyes returned to their normal yellow.
A moment later, Nisi understood what had happened. They all knew that Cayel possessed the strange ability of shadow manipulation, but he rarely used it because most people considered it to be evil and terrifying. However, Nisi didn't know that Cayel could use this ability in any darkness, and from Cayel's reaction, he seemed to be just as surprised.
“Are you okay?” Nisi couldn't help but ask.
“I'm fine. I killed that thing, and I'll be okay soon.” Cayel looked at his “masterpiece,” and then Tenok landed beside him, returning to its original Sbast form.
Now, the monster is no longer moving, and they can finally take a good look at it. Its skin is black and shiny, with a layer of sticky liquid covering it, the mucus firmly attached to the monster's body. It has four wings and four legs, with long, thin claws at the end of each leg, and two straight horns on the skull.
Tenuk and Kayel didn't even have time to ask what this thing was when a monster suddenly leaped out of a nearby thorny bush, screaming loudly. Just then, a familiar car crashed into the side of the monster, which slid a distance before stopping at Nisi's feet. Nisi didn't hesitate, grabbing a shotgun and firing it straight into the monster's head, killing it instantly.
“Oh no...” Retvik muttered to himself as he sat in the driver's seat, then clumsily turned off the engine and climbed down from the truck. “Uh, I didn't mean to. Are you all okay?”
“You missed all the good parts!” Tenuk said with a chuckle. “Where did you go?”
“You left me behind. I've been trying to catch up as fast as I can...” Retvik sighed, then asked, “Excuse me, what are these terrifying things?”
Retvik's problems were answered by Sasarin, who stood up. He was covered in wounds and scratches, looked a bit dazed, but his injuries didn't seem too serious.
“You killed the corrupters! Those infected monsters. When corruption attacked your gods, these creatures were left behind.”
“You mean… we… helped kill the terrifying monster god?” Tenvok stuttered slightly.
“Yes, that's right. There may be more corrupters. But I couldn't shoot them in the head. I don't have a gun. And one against two wouldn't be fair, would it?” Sasarin walked up to Kayel and patted his head. “Thanks you, little guy. You reminded me of my old friend Arctadin. Only you're not as cruel, and you don't have his power to destroy the universe.”
“Uh… thanks… I think… ” Kayel shrugged. “So, uh, did we complete the mission?”
Niccy shrugged, picked up her camera, took a few photos of the definitely dead monsters. Then, she pulled out her favorite dagger – that exquisite Death's Blade, started cutting the horns of one of the monsters, and then went to work on another. However, just as Niccy finished cutting, the monsters suddenly started to combust, quickly turning into a pile of ashes. Niccy's cut horns also turned to ash.
"Well... it's got its pros and cons... " Niccy sighed. "At least I have the photos, though?"
